    rationale: "THE OVULATION INDUCTION MECHANISMS: LETROZOLE (aromatase inhibitor): Aromatase converts androgens → estrogens. Letrozole inhibits aromatase → transient estrogen ↓ in hypothalamus/pituitary → hypothalamus interprets as low estrogen → increases GnRH → increased FSH → follicular development. Critically, when letrozole is discontinued, aromatase recovers → estrogen production normalizes → proper endometrial development. The temporary nature means downstream effects (endometrium, cervical mucus) are NOT impaired. CLOMIPHENE (SERM): Blocks estrogen receptors at hypothalamus/pituitary → brain perceives low estrogen → GnRH/FSH increase → follicular development. BUT clomiphene also blocks ER at endometrium → anti-estrogenic effect → thinner endometrium → hostile to implantation. And blocks ER in cervical glands → thickened cervical mucus → impaired sperm transport. These off-target anti-estrogenic effects explain why clomiphene has a DISCORDANCE between ovulation rate (~80%) and pregnancy rate (~30-40%). PPCOS II TRIAL (2014, NEJM): Letrozole produced significantly higher ovulation rates (61.7% vs 48.3%), pregnancy rates, and live birth rates (27.5% vs 19.1%) than clomiphene in PCOS. Letrozole is now FIRST-LINE per ASRM/ESHRE guidelines.",
